'''Michael Vasileiou''' ({{lang-el|Μιχαήλ Βασιλείου}}) was a [[Greeks|Greek]] 19th-century merchant and benefactor. He was born in [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] occupied [[Gjirokastër]], in modern [[Albania]].

He was the brother of [[Alexandros Vasileiou]], merchant, scholar and student of [[Adamantios Korais]], a major figure of the [[Greek Enlightenment]] movement. Michael Vasileiou ran his trade business in [[Constantinople]] (modern [[Istambul]]), where he lived most of his life and succeeded in becoming one of the most successful businessmen among the members of the [[Ottoman Greeks|Greek community]] in the Ottoman capital.

He supported financially several issues of the ''[[Hermes o Logios]]'' ({{lang-el|Λόγιος Ερμής}}) literary newspaper, published in [[Vienna]] as well the Greek translation of the ''French codex for merchants'' ({{lang-el|Γαλλικός κώδιξ για εμπόρους}}, in 1817).<ref>[http://www.zosimaia.gr/?page=article&id=78 Νεοελληνικός Διαφωτισμός και η Ήπειρος] Σύλλογος Αποφοίτων Ζωσιμαίας Σχολής Ιωαννίνων. [Epirus and the Greek Enlightenment] (Greek)</ref>

Two of his daughters (Efrosyni and Smaragda) married members of the Mellas family, which was also financially strong in the local Greek community of that time.<ref>[http://blacksea.ehw.gr/Forms/filePage.aspx?lemmaId=11164 Οικογένεια Μαύρου]. Ίδρυμα Μείζωνος Ελληνισμού. (Greek)</ref><ref>Sicilianos Demetrios. [https://books.google.com/books?lr=&cd=2&as_brr=0&id=4WloAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22michail+vasileiou%22&q=%22vasileiou%22#search_anchor Old and new Athens]. Putnam, 1960.</ref>

